        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our goal is to map the distribution of cold molecular gas, traced by the 12CO(1-0) emission line, in the nearby spiral galaxy NGC628. We have selected a 5' x 1.5' strip, that covers a range of galactic environments and which can be covered with 50 Nyquist-sampled pointings. 

Based on existing maps, the CO linewidth is known to be small -- &lt; 5 km/s. As such, we request a small bandwidth and high velocity resolution. 

The expected flux density per beam is extimated using existing low resolution CO(1-0) maps, scaled to account for our requested beam size of 2''. Our estimated flux density, based on the HERACLES data of Leroy et al. (2009) ranges from 15mJy-50mJy per 2'' beam. We therefore request a flux sensitivity of 5mJy/beam, in order to achive a S/N of 3-10, in regions of low and high CO surface density respectively. 

We request an angular resolution of 2'', in order to match the resolution of the available ancilliary data. 

The total observing time calculated by the OT is 3.94h (including all calibration and overheads). </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
